            . On the 7th of April I had the burying Mr. Nicholson's wife in the parish of <placeName id="t17700425-12-crimeloc77">St. John's, Southwark</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t17700425-12-crimeloc77" type="placeName" value="St. John's, Southwark"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t17700425-12-crimeloc77" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17700425-12-off75 t17700425-12-crimeloc77"></join>. I being in a back room came forwards, saw the parlour door open, in which the corpse was. I went in, and missed my velvet pall from off the coffin. I was obliged to send and borrow another to perform the burying. I advertised it, and the Monday following came Paget and 
               <persName id="t17700425-12-person226">
                  Thomas
                   Martin
               <interp inst="t17700425-12-person226" type="surname" value="Martin"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17700425-12-person226" type="given" value="Thomas"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17700425-12-person226" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             and informed me it was stole by Farrell from off the coffin, and Martin received it of him, and they went into a field and cut it into seventeen pieces<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="177004250016"></xptr> and carried it to a house in Petticoat-lane, and left it to be disposed of by a Jew. Martin was to have been the chief evidence, and he is set at liberty to discover other robberies, and cannot be found.</p>
